    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow vulnerability in nrLDPC_bnProcPc_BG2_generator_128 due to inconsistent format specifiers\n\n### Summary\nThe LDPC bit node processing generator for BG2 was using inconsistent format specifiers when generating C code for array indexing. This led to potential buffer overflow conditions in the generated code due to undefined behavior in fprintf calls.\n\nSpecifically, some fprintf calls used %u for uint16_t values while others used %d, and similarly for uint32_t values. This inconsistency could cause incorrect array indices to be generated in the output C code.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/CODING/nrLDPC_decoder/nrLDPC_tools/generator_bnProc/bnProcPc_gen_BG2_avx2.c`: Fixed format specifier inconsistencies for lut_startAddrBnGroupsLlr and lut_startAddrBnGroups arrays.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Run the LDPC generator tool to produce the BG2 bit node processing functions\n2. Compile the generated C code with address sanitizer enabled\n3. Execute LDPC decoding with BG2 configuration\n4. Observe potential buffer overflows or memory corruption in the generated functions\n\nThe inconsistent format specifiers cause the generated C code to contain malformed array indexing expressions, which can lead to out-of-bounds memory accesses during LDPC decoding operations.\n"
}